        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName><hi rend="print">Down, | Beckenham, Kent.</hi></placeName>
                    <date>July 8</date>
                    <salute>My dear Sir</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>I must send you one line to thank you for your extremely kind letter &amp; offers of assistance, also for your valuable letter of introduction for my sons, which I have forwarded to them together with your card.—<ref target="#foot.f2"/></p>
<p>Your visit has given me much pleasure,<ref target="#foot.f3"/> &amp; I remain | Yours very sincerely | Ch. Darwin</p> 
                </div>
            </div>

            
            
        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">The year is established by the relationship between this letter and the <ref target="./DCP-LETT-7846F.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter to C. V. Riley, 1 July [1871]</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">Riley’s letters have not been found. George Howard and <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_1222.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Francis Darwin</ref> visited the United States in 1871; see <ref target="./DCP-LETT-7867.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter to Asa Gray, 16 July [1871]</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3">Riley visited Down House on 6 July 1871; see <ref target="./DCP-LETT-7846F.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter to C. V. Riley, 1 July [1871]</ref> and n. 4.</note>
